<exercises xml:id="ex-DefinitionOfLimits">
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Explain in your own words the meaning of:
            <me>
                \lim_{x\to a^-}f(x)=L
            </me>.
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Explain in your own words the meaning of:
            <me>
                \lim_{x\to a^+}f(x)=L
            </me>.
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Explain in your own words the meaning of:
            <me>
                \lim_{x\to a}f(x)=L
            </me>.
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Say we know that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to3^-} f(x)=2</m> and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 3^+}f(x)=2</m>. What do we know (specifically or in general, if anything) about each of the following?
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(3)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    We do not know anything about the value of <m>f(3)</m>, including whether or not there is such a value.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(2.999)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The value of <m>f(2.999)</m> should be close to the number <m>2</m>. We do not know exactly what the value is, though.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(3.001)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The value of <m>f(3.001)</m> should be close to the number <m>2</m>. We do not know exactly what the value is, though.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 3}f(x)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since both the left and the right sided limits are the same single, real number (2), so is the limit: <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 3}f(x)=2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Which of the following is possible? Explain why or why not, and any other conclusions that we can draw.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For some function <m>f(x)</m>, <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 5} f(x)=6</m> and <m>f(5)=-3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is possible.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For some function <m>g(x)</m>, <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4^-} g(x) = -\dfrac{3}{2}</m> and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4^+}g(x) = \dfrac{4}{7}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is possible, although it means that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4}g(x)</m> does not exist.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For some function <m>\ell(t)</m>, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to \alpha} \ell(t) = 2</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to\alpha^+} \ell(t) = 1</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is not possible, since for <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to\alpha} \ell(t) = 2</m> we would need <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to \alpha^+} \ell(t) = 2</m> and <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to \alpha^-} \ell(t) = 2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For some function <m>r(\theta)</m>, <m>\displaystyle\lim_{\theta\to 0}r(\theta)</m> does not exist, <m>\displaystyle\lim_{\theta\to 0^-}r(\theta)=\pi</m>, and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{\theta\to 0^+}r(\theta)=-\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is possible.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For some function <m>j(w)</m>, <m>j(4) = \pi</m> while <m>\displaystyle \lim_{w\to 4}j(w)</m> does not exist.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is possible.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
